Intra- and interspecific variation in Swiss ants

Draft outline

Tim M. Szewczyk

Introduction

The variation of traits within populations is central to many evolutionary and ecological processes, with implications for species coexistence (Violle et al.2012), biogeographical patterns (Classen et al.2017), and responses to anthropogenic change (Moran et al.2016, Merckx et al.2018). Intraspecific variation in morphology can be considerable. In plants, for example, approximately 25% of the trait variation in a typical community is attributable to intraspecific variation (Siefert et al.2015). Incorporating variability among individuals has advanced our understanding of the assembly, structure, and dynamics of communities (Jung et al.2010, Laughlin et al.2012). Nevertheless, intraspecific variability has often been neglected in ecology, and basic patterns for most taxa remain largely unknown (Bolnick et al.2011, Violle et al.2012, Wong and Lewis 2018).

Realized morphological traits result from the interplay of environmental and genetic factors. In eusocial insects like ants, a trait such as body size is the product of intrinsic factors of the colony (e.g., genetics and the social environment), extrinsic factors outside the colony (e.g., available nutrition and the physical environment), and their interaction during larval development (Wills et al.2018). Nevertheless, environmental conditions are expected to be a major driver of the geographical patterns of traits (McGill et al.2006), and many biogeographical rules have been proposed regarding these patterns, often based on physicochemical properties (CITE). For instance, Bergamnns rule asserts an increase in body size in colder environments, and Allens rule a decrease in limb length in colder environments, each based on the reduced heat loss of a smaller surface area to volume ratio (CITE). Similarly, Glogers rule predicts that coloration should be darker in humid environments to counteract the heat capacity of atmospheric moisture (CITE). While many biogeographical rules were originally proposed in particular taxonomic or environmental contexts (CITE), many have since been applied within and among species for a variety of species life styles (CITE).

Traits in insect communities have also been shown to vary along natural and anthropogenic gradients (Reymond et al.2013), sometimes in unexpected ways. For instance, inter- and intraspecific variation in the body size of bees showed opposing patterns on Mount Kilimanjaro, with smaller-bodied species at high elevations, but larger body sizes within species (Classen et al.2017), revealing conflicting pressures of physiological and energetic constraints. In changing environments, the degree of variation within a population may also affect species resilience (Khsel and Blthgen 2015), though empirical evidence is equivocal (Macheriotou et al.2015). Additional anthropogenic impacts like land use change can affect intraspecific variation of particular traits, such as selecting for larger body sizes in moths (Merckx et al.2018), further complicating potential future responses to climate change.

Recent work in ants has shown that morphology indeed varies among communities across environmental gradients. Using species-level average trait values, ant communities tend to become darker in colder environments (Kaspari 2005, Bishop et al 2016), particularly when UV-B is high. Darker species also tend to be larger (Bishop et al 2016). Further, communities in cold environments do not show a uniform shift of the size distribution, but rather a truncation where the smallest species are not present (Reymond et al 2013, Gibb et al 2018). Similarly, wet environments tend to filter out larger species (Gibb et al 2018).

Some work has also explored variation within ant species across elevational gradients. Nevertheless, this work has shown an increase in body size with elevation in one species (Bernadou 2016). In contrast, a broader study of 23 ant species in South Africa found that intraspecific variation was rather small relative to total variation across all species, and found no convincing relationships in intraspecific variation across elevations (Gaudard et al 2019). It is therefore unclear to what extent the patterns of morphology observed among species are also seen within individual species.

Eusocial taxa like ants, however, are in many ways unique due to their colonial life style. In contrast to non-eusocial species, the success of a colony depends on the collective success of the individuals, and thus the distribution of traits within the colony, rather than on any single individual (CITE). Morphological variation within ant colonies can have many implications, including impacts on the thermal foraging window of the colony. In both desert-dwelling Cataglyphis and alpine-dwelling Formica neorufibarbis, larger workers forage during the middle of the day when temperatures are higher because they heat up more slowly (Cerda & Retana 1997, Bernstein 1976). In contrast to patterns in ant communities, the smaller F. neorufibarbis workers in are darker, maximizing their ability to warm up quickly in the cold mornings (Bernstein 1976). Worker-level traits like body size varies among individuals within each colony, with potentially different distributions among colonies within a population and among populations along a gradient (Frenette-Dussault et al.2013, Wills et al.2014, Chevalier et al.2015). Accounting for trait variability among and within ant colonies provides a deeper, more accurate view of the ecological processes shaping communities and biodiversity.

So in this paper, here are the possible topics to include:

  • Basic description with pretty figures showing the distribution of traits among different species
  • Variance partitioning across biological levels
  • Correlations, PCA of traits within workers
  • Hierarchical heteroskedastic regression model assessing drivers
  • When can we ignore variation among colonies? Are there traits where colony identity (and as a corrollary, environment) does not matter? Are there traits where it is particularly important (i.e., colonies are quite distinct)?
  • When can we ignore variation within species? Are there traits or questions where species-level averages are likely to be reasonable approximations of reality? Conversely, are there traits where species-level averages are likely to be poor approximations of reality?

Methods

Model

Overview

This model partitions variation in worker-level traits across multiple biological levels. Here is an online reference with some citations for heteroskedastic models. First, workers are distributed within their colony. We assume that the traits of workers within each colony follow a normal distribution about a colony-level mean with a colony-level standard deviation. This is empirically not true for all species, species that are polymorphic or dimorphic. For workers in the minor caste or for workers of monomorphic species, however, this is a reasonable simplifying assumption.

The colony-level mean and standard deviation may vary with the environment. Thats what were testing. However, there are other factors beyond the available environmental variables that may influence these values, including stochasticity. Thus, we construct separate regressions for the mean and standard deviation, where each includes environmental variables and normally distributed random error. Lastly, we allow each species to respond differently to each environmental variable (i.e., random intercept and random slopes), but these responses are taxonomically clustered such that information is shared among species, with greater influence among species within the same genus.

Model structure

The trait value for each worker \(i\) is distributed normally within each colony \(j\) for each species \(s\) such that:

\[\begin{equation} y_{i,j,s} \sim Norm(\bar{y}_{j,s}, d_{j,s}) \end{equation}\]

where \(\bar{y}_{j,s}\) is the intra-colony mean, and \(d_{j,s}\) is the intra-colony standard deviation. We use robust regression to predict the underlying relationships between the environment and the colony-level parameters to allow for fatter tails in the residual distributions. Each intra-colony mean is therefore distributed about predicted value \(\mu_{j,s}\) based on the environmental conditions such that:

\[\begin{equation} \bar{y}_{j,s} \sim Student\text{-}t(\mu_{j,s}, \sigma_{1}, \nu_{1}) \end{equation}\]

\[\begin{equation} \mu_{j,s} = X_j b_s \end{equation}\]

where scale \(\sigma_{1}\) and degrees of freedom \(\nu_{1}\) are parameters describing the shape of the Student-t distribution, \(X\) is a matrix of environmental covariates, and \(b\) is a vector of species specific slopes.

Similarly, the within-colony variation is expected to be a function of the environment. Thus, the standard deviation within each colony \(d_{j,s}\) is:

\[\begin{equation} log(d_{j,s}) \sim Student\text{-}t(\delta_{j,s}, \sigma_{2}, \nu_{2}) \end{equation}\]

\[\begin{equation} \delta_{j,s} = V_j a_s \end{equation}\]

where scale \(\sigma_{2}\) and degrees of freedom \(\nu_{2}\) again describe the shape of the Student-t distribution, \(V\) is a matrix of environmental covariates, and \(a_s\) is a vector of species specific slopes.

Thus, we assume that the both the intra-colony means and standard deviations may vary with environmental conditions. The hierarchical priors on \(b\) and \(a\) allow for taxonomic clustering among genera:

\[\begin{equation} b_{p,s} \sim Norm(B_{p,g}, \sigma_{b_p}) \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} B_{g} \sim mvNorm(\beta, \Sigma_B) \end{equation}\]

\[\begin{equation} a_{p,s} \sim Norm(A_{p,g}, \sigma_{a_p}) \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} A_{g} \sim mvNorm(\alpha, \Sigma_A) \end{equation}\]

where \(B_{g}\) and \(A_{g}\) are genus-level averages with standard deviations \(\sigma_{b_p}\) and \(\sigma_{A_p}\) for each variable \(p\), and \(\beta\) and \(\alpha\) are overall average responses among all species with covariance matrices \(\Sigma_B\) and \(\Sigma_A\).

Scratch

Within-colony variation

We expect that, on average, the variation within each colony will be underestimated. With only four workers from each colony, the sample size is quite small. This biases the standard deviation of the sample downward. For example, say we have a large colony with a trait that follows a standard normal distribution. We can take many samples of 4 workers and calculate the standard deviation of each sample:

sd_true <- 0.1
wkr_samples <- map_dbl(1:1e2, ~sd(rnorm(4, 0, sd_true)))

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(density(wkr_samples), main="Simulated sd for samples of 4 workers", 
     xlab="Sample sd")
abline(v=sd_true, col="red")
abline(v=exp(mean(log(wkr_samples))), col="blue", lty=2)

plot((wkr_samples - sd_true), main="Residuals", col=rgb(0,0,0,0.05),
     xlab="Sample", ylab=expression(s-sigma))
abline(h=0, col="red")
abline(h=mean(wkr_samples - sd_true), col="blue", lty=2)

# Proportion of samples underestimating true sd
round(sum(wkr_samples < sd_true)/length(wkr_samples), 3)
## [1] 0.62

Thus, we should expect that, on average, the latent predicted within-colony standard deviation \(d\) is larger than the standard deviation of the four measurements. More specifically, it should be something like 60% that underestimate it. This is a function of the sample size, rather than the standard deviation, at least assuming that the observations are, in fact, drawn from a normal distribution.

sim.df <- expand.grid(N=c(2,3,4,10), 
                      sd_true=seq(0.01, 2, length.out=6), 
                      sim=1:1e2) %>%
  pmap_dfr(., function(N, sd_true, sim) tibble(N=N, 
                                               sd_true=sd_true, 
                                               sd_sample=sd(rnorm(N, 0, sd_true)))) %>%
  mutate(N=as.factor(N))
ggplot(sim.df, aes(sd_sample, colour=N)) + 
  geom_vline(data=summarise(group_by(sim.df, N, sd_true), 
                            N=first(N), sd_true=first(sd_true)), 
             aes(xintercept=sd_true), lty=3) +
  geom_density() + 
  scale_colour_viridis_d(end=0.8) + facet_wrap(~sd_true, scales="free")

# Proportion of samples underestimating true sd
sim.df %>% group_by(N, sd_true) %>%
  summarise(pr_under=sum(sd_sample < sd_true)/n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(sd_true, pr_under, colour=N)) + geom_line() +
  scale_colour_viridis_d(end=0.8)

So this means we would expect that the residuals between \(sd(y_{1-4,j,s})\) and \(d_{j,s}\) should be biased toward \(d_{j,s}\) being larger (i.e., negative). In the current formulation with an approximate run, this is true, with \(sd(y_{1-4,j,s}) < d_{j,s}\) for about 67% of the colonies. This is maybe a bit more biased toward predicting a larger standard deviation, but I think is not too bad, considering that not all colonies have four workers (mean: 3.88; 7 with 1 worker, 2 with 2 workers, 3 with 6 workers, and 239 with 4 workers).

Alternative model formulation

The above equations could also be re-written in a different formulation that involves fewer equations, though Im not sure its more intuitive:

\[\begin{equation} y_{i,j,s} = X_j b_s + \sigma_{1,s}\epsilon_{1,j} + e^{V_j a_s + \sigma_{2,s}\epsilon_{2,j}}\epsilon_{1,i} \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} \epsilon_{1,j} \sim Norm(0, 1) \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} \epsilon_{1,i} \sim Norm(0, 1) \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} \epsilon_{2,j} \sim Norm(0, 1) \end{equation}\]

with species-level errors \(\epsilon_{1,j}\) and \(\epsilon_{2,j}\), and worker-level error \(\epsilon_{1,i}\).

It might be clearer to break that up a bit: \[\begin{equation} y_{i,j,s} = \bar{y}_{j,s} + d_{j,s}\epsilon_{1,i} \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} \bar{y}_{j,s} = X_j b_s + \sigma_{1,s}\epsilon_{1,j} \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} log(d_{j,s}) = V_j a_s + \sigma_{2,s}\epsilon_{2,j} \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} \epsilon_{1,j} \sim Norm(0, 1) \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} \epsilon_{1,i} \sim Norm(0, 1) \end{equation}\] \[\begin{equation} \epsilon_{2,j} \sim Norm(0, 1) \end{equation}\]

Prediction notes

Given the assemblage-level work using species-level averages, theres also the question of whether individual workers (or colonies) that are darker tend to be larger, and whether this corresponds with workers (or colonies) from colder environments. There is also a question of timing, where the size or color of workers could change with either the age of the individual worker (light just after eclosion, and possibly also fading with age?) or the date of eclosion (larvae developing at different points in the summer, fed different diets, experiencing different temperatures). For predictions based on date or season, I think I need to do more research.

Combining everything, the predictions could be:

  1. In cold environments:
    1. Size
      • colony means are larger
      • q05 is larger, q95 is unchanged (?)
      • colony sd is larger (but conflicts with previous)
    2. Color
      • colony means are darker
      • colony sd is larger
    3. Relative Leg Length
      • colony means are smaller
    4. Relative Scape Length
      • colony means are smaller
  2. In wet environments:
    1. Size
      • colony means are smaller
      • q05 is unchanged, q95 is smaller (?)
    2. Color
      • colony means are darker
  3. In early season:
    1. Size
    2. Color
      • colony sd is larger at end of season (?)
  4. In highly variable environments:
    1. Size
      • colony sd is larger
    2. Color
      • colony sd is larger
  5. Size and color:
    1. Larger workers are darker
    2. Colonies with larger means have darker means
  6. Predictions based on foraging habits?
    1. Species/genera that forage in open are more exposed
    2. Species in forests are less exposed
    3. Variation has larger impact for larger taxa?
      • a 10% change in size is physiologically more consequential for larger sizes
